description: Steven Weissman won the Harvey Award for "Best New Talent" in 1998, and Fantagraphics Books is now proud to present Don't Call Me Stupid!, a collection of the comics that garnered him this outrageously prestigious honor. The first book in the "Yikes" series, serving as a perfect introduction to the cast, has plenty to laugh at and includes such "Yikes" "classics" as "James Watch," "Back in the Day" and the title story, "Don't Call Me Stupid!" As funny as it is, though, "Don't Call Me Stupid" is an insightful book about childhood friendships, with their attendant sorrows, suicide, contagious disease, vandalism, theft, grudges, abuse, dismemberment, broken homes, murder, insanity, romance, video games and cigarette smoking. But it's funny! Each story is printed in Weissman's patented two-color "chubby format." This collection of "Tykes" strips is sure to leave readers of all ages laughing for more. Each of the gang takes a turn at the spotlight here: Li'l Bloody, the Pull-Apart Boy, X-Ray Spence, Dead Boy and the rest of the mischievous young monsters cavort and explore one of the strangest neighborhoods in funnybookland. We'd give this one a "PG" for cartoon violence and smoking, but don't let that scare you, kids â pick up a copy, and discover why Weissman counts the Hernandez Brothers among his biggest fans!

description:
"'Fucussle'?! What's that mean?"

"No, it's Fuck You, Asshole! by Johnny Ryan."

Thus begins the fourth and final collection of comic strips starring the stupidest, ugliest, stubbliest girl in grade number two. Blecky and her "pals" are back and so are the fountains of blood, urine, and other bodily fluids (not to mention profanity) in these riotously hilarious, eye-poppingly offensive four-panel gag strips. Co-starring the usual cast of Blecky's weirdo friends and enemies, plus douching robots, the Christmas barbarian, the world's most bad-ass Easter basket, the Spamfs, 69-11, sexy murder hunks, ass worship, glory holes, the Pizzazooka, Dizzy the herpes-sniffing dog, Sir Oreo Monocle and oh so much more. Over 100 pages of ridiculous absurdity, over-the-top grossouts, and scathing satire that could only come from the mind and pen of Johnny Ryan.

description: In 1950, writers Arnold Drake and Leslie Waller, both attending college on the G.I. Bill, envisioned a sophisticated, novel-length comic tailored to their peers. Collaborating with comics art master Matt Baker, known for singularly defining the genre of "good girl art" on titles such as Phantom Lady, they crafted a film-noir inspired masterwork of romance, intrigue, and moral relativity. When cynical newspaperman Hal Weber reunites with old flame Rust Masson, he finds the beguiling widow of a mining magnate willing to do anything to undermine the local political machine--her only opponent for total control of Copper City! This painstakingly restored replica volume includes a new introduction by writer Arnold Drake providing a first-hand history of the graphic novel. Before winning the Bill Finger Award for lifetime achievement in comics writing, before creatingDeadman, or writing Doom Patrol and X-Men, Drake helped bring the original "picture novel" to life, a true milestone in the history of comics!
name: TPB
